WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Next up, we have Gordon Shotwell, who's going to be talking to us about why technical debt is a social problem.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Hi. Thank you so much for coming.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:38.000
So the title of this talk is Technical Debt is a Social Problem.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:48.000
And the reason I wanted to give that is I think, unfortunately, our community has a reputation, especially in industry, as a language that has a high amount of technical debt.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:56.000
I think this is actually a fairly major problem in terms of adopting R in a lot of contexts where it hasn't been adopted before.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:59.000
And as a community, we need to take this seriously and work on it.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:12.000
And I've often found myself in the position where I was kind of coming into a team or an organization, and I knew sort of what to do to pay back technical debt on that team.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:17.000
But I didn't actually have any sort of decision-making power over what we worked on.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:22.000
So I had to sort of learn to be a little bit more strategic in terms of building these more robust solutions.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.000
And the main insight that I had through this process was that it's not a technical problem, really.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:30.000
It's a social problem.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:43.000
Technical debt, for those of you who are not familiar, basically all of the little shortcuts that we take developing things, especially under time pressure, that make the products less stable or less easy to maintain over the long term.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.000
The idea is that eventually you're going to pay that back.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:47.000
That's the idea.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.000
It's really the practice.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:56.000
And when you look at the actual artifacts that we call technical debt, they're almost always social artifacts.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:59.000
And I think they fall into two main categories.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:03.000
They're a failure of consideration or a failure of communication.

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Sorry, the other way around on the slide.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:06.000
Read the slides.

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Don't listen to me.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:10.000
So communication is really just what you think about it.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
It's how we communicate technically with other people.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:21.000
So the things that fall into this category are, like, documentation, which is how we communicate use and purpose.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Tests, which is how we communicate correctness, like what the software is meant to do precisely.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:32.000
And then also things like code style and project organization.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:40.000
How easy it is to find the thing that you're looking for in a code project and how easy it is to understand that thing, to actually just physically read it.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.000
So those are all quite obviously, I think, things that happen between other people.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:53.000
We can't judge whether documentation is good or bad without knowing whether another human being who's relevant to us understands it, right?

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:57.000
There's no, like, perfect communication that we can transmit to the world.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:01.000
What matters is whether somebody understands us.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:08.000
Consideration are all the things that have to do with how well your software handles things that are not problems that you have, right?

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Whenever we're developing software, it does a really good job of handling the problem that's in front of us, the problem that we're thinking about.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:25.000
But we can judge software as being kind of good or bad, robust or not, based on how it sort of handles a broader spectrum of people, right?

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.000
So these are things like the code isn't robust, right?

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Someone throws some arguments at it that you didn't really think about, that weren't something that you would think to throw at a function, and it all falls down.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:43.000
It can't be updated easily. Maybe there's a lot of repetition and things need to be updated in many places, right?

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:48.000
It doesn't solve the problems of future people, or even just the problems of other people today.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:56.000
And then it has things like fragile dependency structures, or maybe it works on some scales, but it doesn't work at all on larger scales.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:03.000
So all of these are basically about how good our imagination is when we're developing these products, right?

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:08.000
How well we can think about all the different things that somebody might conceivably throw at that,

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:15.000
and how skilled we are at putting ourselves in other people's shoes to understand how they're going to relate to that problem,

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
what they're going to try to solve with it, and how they're going to try to solve it.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:21.000
So again, these are really social problems, right?

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:28.000
It's not so much that there's a perfect dependency structure, it's not that there's a perfect kind of robustness.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:35.000
It has to do with how we're considering the needs of other people in our organization and the people who will join it in the future.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:43.000
So this also gives us some insight into why it's so difficult to pay technical debt back, right?

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
Because when you realize that actually this is a problem between two people,

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.000
you sort of bring in this other insight, which is that people are really kind of fickle and biased, right?

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:57.000
So some of the biases that I think you encounter, so one of them is status quo bias.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:02.000
This is, of course, the 1970s UK rock band, Status Quo. I'm sure it's familiar to you.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:08.000
So this is just that when you're working with a system for long enough, right,

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:13.000
you've paid the price of learning that system, and you've kind of gotten used to the pain you feel when you use it, right?

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
So it's sort of all those things kind of disappear for you.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
And so you have this sort of bias that you kind of like the way it is, right,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.000
and you're not going to really be that interested in changing it.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:28.000
You're going to sort of overestimate the cost of change because you've already learned the existing thing,

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:33.000
and nobody's learned the new things, or you're going to have to do some work to learn the new thing.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
The second bias is the IKEA effect, and this is one of my favorites.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.000
I love this picture because you can really tell that she likes that chair.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:46.000
So when you build something from IKEA, basically you overestimate how good it is.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:50.000
So you put something together yourself, and you kind of invest a little bit of your ego into that thing,

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:55.000
and since your ego is your favorite thing, suddenly that thing becomes way better than everything else.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:01.000
I think this is a big part of why programmers tend to like building their own databases, right?

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Because even if it's worse objectively than the database you could buy, you built it,

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:09.000
so there's some pride that goes along with that.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:12.000
So similarly, whenever you're trying to replace something,

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:17.000
usually you're replacing something that somebody in your organization who's still there has built, right?

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:19.000
So they overvalue it.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
And lastly, it's the parenting effect.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
This is my daughter's first experience with spinach.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:26.000
And so this is...

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
When you watch something grow up, you forgive its messes, right?

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.000
You forgive the problems because you knew...

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
You sort of see how it's sort of progressed over time,

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.000
and you're like, well, it's so much better than it used to be, right?

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:40.000
This system can do so much more than it used to be.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
It's so much easier to use than it used to be.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.000
And you sort of forget about that actually right now it's got some problems.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
So all of these things together, I'm sure we could think of other biases,

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:56.000
but all of these things together means that it's never a fair contest, right?

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:59.000
Whenever you're trying to pay back technical debt,

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.000
it's not that people are going to rationally evaluate,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:04.000
like, which one is objectively a little bit better, right?

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.000
When you're replacing these things, you have to do much, much better

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:12.000
in order to get over these kinds of humps that you find within an organization.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:17.000
And the goal, I think, for doing that is to try to build delightful products.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:19.000
So something where...

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.000
This is sort of similar to how we relate with external users of products, right?

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:26.000
We want to build something that actually people get excited about when they use,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:27.000
that they really sort of...

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.000
It's a joyful experience when they use this thing.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
And that can mean a lot of different things.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
For me, like, some of the things I really focus on are

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:39.000
that it sets up in a single step, so like install.packages, right?

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:43.000
You only have to call one thing, and the setup is complete.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:47.000
There's a clear, obvious first problem.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:48.000
There's a way to...

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:51.000
Kind of a clear way to get from the obvious first problem

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:55.000
to something quite complicated to be a master of that system.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:01.000
And then it has sort of help resources, and it doesn't break, right?

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
It doesn't sort of just randomly stop working.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:04.000
So one of the things...

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:08.000
One of the products I really love that fulfills all these things is R Markdown

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
because especially it sort of gives you something that, like, right away,

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
here's the easy thing that you can do right now.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:19.000
But down the road, you know, you can just really take over all publishing, you know?

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:21.000
Like, you can publish all the websites, all the books, right?

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:26.000
Using the same framework, and there's a smooth path to that.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:27.000
So building delightful products.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:28.000
That's the goal.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
And if you do that, then I think you can kind of overcome those biases.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:33.000
How do you build delightful products?

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.000
Well, I have a three-step plan for you.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:39.000
So the first one is to find the right beachhead,

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
which is to pick your first battle in this process of paying that technical debt

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:45.000
and pick that correctly.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Second is to separate users and maintainers

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:51.000
and to treat these internal products more like you treat external pacing products.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:54.000
And lastly, empathize with the debtor.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:59.000
So a beachhead, for those of you who are not familiar with the military things,

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.000
is like when you're invading a country,

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.000
you, like, have, like, a little staging area that you have to take first, right?

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.000
So it's not about winning the war, but it's about, like,

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
putting yourself in a position where you can, you know,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:13.000
deploy your resources and, you know, get supply lines and all that stuff.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:15.000
So finding the right beachhead is very much about, like,

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
picking the right project.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
And so this is a picture of a piece of code base

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:25.000
that I was working on at Socure when I was first starting,

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:26.000
and each of these is an R script.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:27.000
Each of the dots is an R script,

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.000
and each of the lines is a sourcing relationship

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:32.000
between the script and another one.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
And Socure at the time was a very small data science team

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:37.000
and has grown a lot,

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.000
so this was a kind of type of way of sharing code

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
that works really pretty well if you're, like, four or five people.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:46.000
It works less well if you're, like, 25 or 30 people.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:50.000
And there's a sort of natural tendency for myself to, like,

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:51.000
look at this and say,

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
I just need to replace this with a package, right?

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:56.000
I need to take over all of this code and put it into one thing.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And that's going to fail, right?

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
Because there's no way that I'm going to be able to really understand

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:02.000
what each of these things does,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:04.000
and there's no way that actually I even know

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:07.000
that a lot of these things need to be around at all, right?

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:09.000
So you have to be strategic about what you're picking.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.000
Which of these am I going to use to give me kind of something

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:14.000
which I know I'm going to be able to accomplish,

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:18.000
and it's also going to build trust in the organization.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:20.000
So some of these things I think it's really important to focus on

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:22.000
small, contained projects,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:24.000
and something that you can do really, really well at, right?

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
You're trying to knock it out of the park,

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
and it's easier to do that with a baseball

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.000
than like a bag of Jell-O or, you know, an elephant or something, right?

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:33.000
So you want to have something that's small,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
because mostly what's going to happen

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
is people are going to judge it based on the delta,

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
not so much the overall value.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
So it's better to do really, really well in an area of limited scope

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:46.000
than just a little bit well in an area of big scope.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
It's good if it's an orphan or greenfield project,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
like there's nobody in the organization who's super attached

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
to how it's like now.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:56.000
And if there's external pressure coming from outside of your team,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:57.000
that's also really great,

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
because nobody likes to respond to that.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.000
So if you can take that on, it's really good.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
So in my case, what we picked there

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
was the database access functions, right?

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
They were small, I could understand them well,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
and we were responding to some external pressure

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
from our infrastructure team to sort of change

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
how we were storing and distributing credentials.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.000
So find the right beachhead.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:19.000
Put yourself in a position where you can solve this small problem

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:22.000
and solve it well so that you can move forward.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
And what this will allow you to do

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.000
is develop trust within the organization.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
It'll allow you to build up the social

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.000
and sort of technical infrastructure that you need

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
to solve these problems, like a CI process

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:37.000
or just learning how to do code review with other people.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:41.000
The second main point is to separate users and maintainers.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
And this is in order to build delightful products,

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.000
you need somebody who is defining what delight means

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
and you need somebody who's trying to make the product do that, right?

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
So in other words, you need a user and you need a maintainer.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
So ideally, every system in your team or your organization

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:57.000
should have a written-down list

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.000
of who is a maintainer of that product

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
and everybody else is a user.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
These two groups abide by a basic and holy contract.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
That contract is that users get coddled

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
and maintainers get opinions, right?

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
So you have to pick one of these things.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
And we all want to kind of sit between these.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:17.000
Like, we want to be coddled, and we also want to have opinions.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
We want to make these decisions,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
but we don't really want to deal with all the consequences

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
that might happen down the road from those decisions.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
We don't want to write the code,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
we don't want to document it or write tests.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:30.000
What this says is basically we're not doing that anymore

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
with these sort of low-technical problems.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:35.000
We're going to have maintainers and we're going to have users.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
And if you're a user and you want to be a maintainer,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:39.000
you're welcome to, but you're going to get

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
all of the other stuff that goes along with that

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.000
to make sure that this product is delightful.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
So being a good maintainer means

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
that you're responsible for making it delightful.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
That's your goal, right?

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
You want to make this product really, really good,

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
really, really easy to use. You want to make it a joy.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
With that, you have the responsibility

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
and the authority to do that, right?

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
So you're the decision-maker over what that product does

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
and how it does it, right?

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
You decide how it's going to accomplish this goal,

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
and you kind of judge yourself

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
based on whether you're accomplishing it.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
So along with this means that you don't kind of ask

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
the users to do your job for you.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:17.000
This comes up a lot for internal products with documentation,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:20.000
where the first time that we ask somebody to set up a system,

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
and if the documentation is wrong,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.000
we ask that person to fix the documentation,

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
when usually, actually, they're the worst person

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
to document something because they understand it the least.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
So this is sort of something where you say,

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
like, as a maintainer, I'm going to do all of this stuff

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
to make sure that this thing is really good,

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
and I'm not going to expect the user

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:40.000
to be able to do any of the things that I should do.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
Being a good user is basically the opposite of this, right?

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.000
You get to define what delight means,

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
and importantly, you have to sort of turn off

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
the part of your brain that can understand

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
computer systems really, really well.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.000
So as developers, like, it's tempting to basically be like,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
oh, I have a bug with a system I don't maintain.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:00.000
I'm going to go read the source code and figure out what that bug is.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
And that's rarely a good use of your time,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
both because you have your own systems to maintain,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:07.000
and also because you're not actually fixing the problem

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:11.000
for the sort of, like, lowest common denominator user, right?

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
You want to have the feedback be like,

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.000
actually, this was hard to use.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.000
I had to think hard to get this to set up.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
Please fix that, right?

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
That's not delightful if I have to work too hard at it.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.000
It's also good to ask about the problem, not the solution.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
So rather than proposing, like, you should change

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
this technical thing in your system,

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
say, like, as a user, I have this problem, right?

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
There's a reason why product managers use that a lot.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
It's a really good way of phrasing it.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
And it's just important to not be embarrassed

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
about complaining about something

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
and to really try to never read source code.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
So a good sort of standard is,

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
if you're asked to do, like, documentation,

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:49.000
like, you can ask, you can give code-style input,

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
and if people, like, say, like, we're not talking about that,

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
that means you're a user.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
So, for instance, like, sometimes I start asking,

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:58.000
like, you know, like, some of these questions,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:01.000
and then eventually they say, like, you know,

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.000
I actually start talking about something else,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:05.000
and then I say, okay, great, I'm a user.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:09.000
Like, you know, fix your docs.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
So another sort of thing that comes up frequently

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:13.000
is, like, I run an R package,

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
and I often get sort of requests

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
from various different people

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
to put a function that they've written into that R package.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
And this might be a perfectly good function

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
that solves the problem that's in front of them.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
But it might not be tested.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.000
It might not be consistent with the other functions.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:28.000
It might not be documented.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:29.000
So if you do that too much,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:31.000
you kind of end up with this sort of package, right,

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:33.000
where you sort of, like, you know,

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
you've made some progress, like, you've lined them up, right?

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
But it's actually, it's never going to really do the job.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
Like, doing the job of building

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:41.000
sort of a global system that works well together

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
and is intuitive and easy to remember,

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.000
it takes a lot of work, right?

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
You actually have to think hard about it.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
And unless you're a maintainer of this package,

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.000
you're not really going to have the time

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
or attention to do that, right?

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:59.000
So the last point is to empathize with the debtor.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
And I think the important thing here

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:06.000
is whenever you're doing these projects,

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:09.000
you kind of have to, like, remember

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:12.000
that what you're doing is kind of inherently threatening

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
and sort of insulting, right?

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
Because you're saying to somebody

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
who has worked hard on something, right,

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
that the thing that they've developed, like,

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
doesn't work anymore, right?

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:24.000
Or maybe it never worked, but it doesn't work anymore.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:27.000
And that is really a problem

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
because you're also asking them to learn something.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
And when people are sort of threatened or afraid,

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
it turns out that they can't learn anything, right?

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.000
Those two parts of your mind, like,

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:39.000
they can't work together.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
So you need to have people be kind of, like,

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:45.000
comfortable and feel supported and understood

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.000
in order to get them to change

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
and also in order for you to learn from them, right?

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.000
Because the existing products, like, they're not all bad.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:53.000
They've done some good jobs, right?

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
So it's important to, like,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.000
to really, like, try to take their perspective

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
to understand, like, where they're coming from,

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:02.000
why does this system do things the way it does,

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:06.000
and how can we kind of together make it better?

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:08.000
And then more often than not, this is you, right?

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:10.000
Like, you're looking at your own projects

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:13.000
from two years ago, paying back technical debt,

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.000
and you kind of don't want to look at it

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.000
because you feel bad about yourself,

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:20.000
and that's unpleasant, so you never fix the tests, right?

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:23.000
Like, you know, so having this, like,

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
I'm kind of using this phrase to, like,

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
talk about other people, but really a lot of the times

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
it's you, right? Like, you're the person

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:31.000
on the other side of this when you have some other person

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
coming in and saying, like, this doesn't work,

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.000
or you're looking at your old stuff and it doesn't work.

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
And all this really applies in the same way, right?

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
Like, you're trying to learn a new thing,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
and if you feel threatened and afraid,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
you're not going to learn it, right?

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
You're just going to kind of, like, whatever.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:47.000
The docs are fine.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
So...

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
There's this...

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
I don't know if you're familiar with Marie Kondo,

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.000
but she has this thing where you, like,

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
if you're getting rid of your old pants,

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
like, you pick up your pants and you say,

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
you know, thank you, pants.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
Like, you know, you covered my butt for a lot.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
You know, like, you did a good job, right?

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
And then that helps you let go,

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
because you're sort of like, these don't look good on me anymore,

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
but thank you.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:17.000
So I really think that one way of developing

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:20.000
this kind of empathy

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.000
is to look at technical bad as a good sign.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
And the reason it's a good sign

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:30.000
is because the only reason you ever care about paying back debt

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
is if you haven't declared bankruptcy, right?

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.000
So, you know, technical debt means, like,

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
I haven't declared technical or regular bankruptcy, right?

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.000
So there's still something there to work on, right?

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
Otherwise I just throw it away.

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:45.000
So you can look at all these code sort of artifacts,

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
these things that, you know, you're like,

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
oh, this is awful, this is really fragile,

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
it breaks all the time, it's hard to learn.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.000
And sort of just remember that actually this is

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.000
the work of, like, thoughtful people

00:18:57.000 --> 00:19:00.000
who are doing their best with the knowledge and resources

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:02.000
that they have available to them.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:04.000
And that's really all we can ask of people.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:07.000
And similarly, the code,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
the fact that you're looking at that code or that product

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:12.000
means that it got you to the next step, right?

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:15.000
It did something.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.000
And even if that thing is just basically

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
showing you what doesn't work, right?

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
And that's really all we can ask of these products

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:24.000
is just to take us one step forward

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:27.000
so that we can, like, fix it, right?

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
It's kind of a constant process

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
of just basically fixing broken things

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:34.000
and then breaking new things that need fixing later.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:37.000
So going back to this slide, basically...

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
Sorry, I was not using a timer.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
Going back to this slide,

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
this code base was developed at a time

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.000
when Sokir was really kind of in a slight, like, emergency.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:48.000
Like, we really needed a product to get to market, right?

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:50.000
And this did that, right?

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
We have a market-leading identity product now

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
because of what this code did, right?

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
Even it's a bit of a tangled mess.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
Like, it got us there, and that's why I'm here

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
sort of talking about this.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.000
So thank you.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.000
That's all I really have.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:06.000
I think it's a sort of important thing that we should focus on.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:08.000
We are hiring, so please talk to me

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:10.000
if you would like to work on identity fraud.

00:20:10.000 --> 00:20:12.000
And I'm on Twitter.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:14.000
Thank you.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
Oh, sorry.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:19.000
That's wrong.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:21.000
Thank you, Gordon.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
We have time for maybe one question.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
Regarding the user versus maintainer roles,

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
what are tips for teams with high turnover?

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:29.000
And then another question is...

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.000
Oops.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:33.000
Where a team has a user that is highly likely

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:35.000
to become a future maintainer.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:37.000
So for the turnover,

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:39.000
I think basically turnover is good

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:41.000
because the more turnover you have,

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:43.000
the more education feedback you get.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:45.000
So in that sense, it's important, basically,

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:47.000
like, if you're able to manage high turnover,

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:49.000
that's a good sign that you're able

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
to educate people quickly.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:53.000
So that's actually kind of like a beneficial thing.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
For the maintainer user things,

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:57.000
I think kind of giving people, like,

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:59.000
good first projects is really helpful.

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:01.000
One of the things that I think is...

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.000
I found very helpful, personally,

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:05.000
is if somebody else writes tests for me.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:07.000
So if somebody else writes tests for me,

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:09.000
I think that's really helpful.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.000
If somebody else writes tests for me.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.000
So if you're a senior person,

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:15.000
the best thing you can do

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:17.000
is write documentation or tests

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:19.000
and have a junior person fill in the code.

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:21.000
Like, the code is actually the easiest part.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:23.000
Setting the expectations for what that code

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:25.000
needs to do is the hard part.

00:21:25.000 --> 00:21:27.000
Great. Thank you very much.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:29.000
Thank you.

